<!-- FAQ -->
<section class="sec bg-white relative py-16">
 <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6">
 <h2 class="text-3xl lg:text-4xl font-black text-slate-900 uppercase italic tracking-tighter mb-10 text-center">Laptop Power Bank <span class="text-brandOrange">FAQ</span></h2>
 <div class="space-y-4">
 <details class="bg-slate-50 rounded-xl p-5 border border-slate-200 group">
 <summary class="font-black text-slate-900 cursor-pointer flex justify-between items-center text-sm uppercase">Can a laptop power bank charge a MacBook Pro?<span class="text-brandOrange group-open:rotate-180 transition">▼</span></summary>
 <p class="faq-answer text-slate-600 text-sm leading-relaxed mt-4">Yes. Models with 67W or higher PD output (WOP21, WOP22, WOP23) charge MacBook Pro 13/14/16-inch at full speed. The WOP23 240W PD 3.1 model also supports MacBook Pro 16-inch fast charging at 140W, matching Apple's MagSafe 3 charger output.</p>
 </details>
 <details class="bg-slate-50 rounded-xl p-5 border border-slate-200 group">
 <summary class="font-black text-slate-900 cursor-pointer flex justify-between items-center text-sm uppercase">What is PD 3.1 vs PD 3.0?<span class="text-brandOrange group-open:rotate-180 transition">▼</span></summary>
 <p class="faq-answer text-slate-600 text-sm leading-relaxed mt-4">PD 3.0 caps at 100W maximum output. PD 3.1 (released 2021) extends the standard up to 240W using new 28V, 36V, and 48V voltage rails (Extended Power Range, EPR). PD 3.1 is required for charging gaming laptops and 16-inch MacBook Pro at full speed.</p>
 </details>
 <details class="bg-slate-50 rounded-xl p-5 border border-slate-200 group">
 <summary class="font-black text-slate-900 cursor-pointer flex justify-between items-center text-sm uppercase">Is a 27000mAh laptop power bank airline safe?<span class="text-brandOrange group-open:rotate-180 transition">▼</span></summary>
 <p class="faq-answer text-slate-600 text-sm leading-relaxed mt-4">Yes. 27000mAh at 3.7V equals 99.9Wh, just under the 100Wh IATA carry-on limit. All WOWOHCOOL laptop power banks are UN38.3 certified and approved for air carry-on. Anything above 100Wh requires airline approval and is forbidden in checked baggage.</p>
 </details>
 <details class="bg-slate-50 rounded-xl p-5 border border-slate-200 group">
 <summary class="font-black text-slate-900 cursor-pointer flex justify-between items-center text-sm uppercase">What is the MOQ for laptop power bank OEM?<span class="text-brandOrange group-open:rotate-180 transition">&#9660;</span></summary>
 <p class="faq-answer text-slate-600 text-sm leading-relaxed mt-4">MOQ starts at 500 units for standard ODM models with custom logo printing. Custom OEM with tooling: 1,000-2,000 units. Sample turnaround: 3-7 days for standard, 10-15 days for custom.</p>
 </details>
 <details class="bg-slate-50 rounded-xl p-5 border border-slate-200 group">
 <summary class="font-black text-slate-900 cursor-pointer flex justify-between items-center text-sm uppercase">How long does a 27000mAh power bank charge a MacBook Pro?<span class="text-brandOrange group-open:rotate-180 transition">&#9660;</span></summary>
 <p class="faq-answer text-slate-600 text-sm leading-relaxed mt-4">A 27000mAh (99.9Wh) power bank provides approximately 1.3-1.5 full charges for a MacBook Pro 14" (70Wh battery) or about 0.7-0.8 charges for a MacBook Pro 16" (100Wh battery). With 85% conversion efficiency, expect 85Wh usable energy from a 99.9Wh bank.</p>
 </details>
 <details class="bg-slate-50 rounded-xl p-5 border border-slate-200 group">
 <summary class="font-black text-slate-900 cursor-pointer flex justify-between items-center text-sm uppercase">Can I charge a laptop and phone simultaneously?<span class="text-brandOrange group-open:rotate-180 transition">&#9660;</span></summary>
 <p class="faq-answer text-slate-600 text-sm leading-relaxed mt-4">Yes. All WOWOHCOOL laptop power banks support simultaneous multi-device output. The WOP23 can deliver 240W to a laptop while charging a phone via secondary USB-C or USB-A port. Total output is dynamically allocated across ports.</p>
 </details>
 <details class="bg-slate-50 rounded-xl p-5 border border-slate-200 group">
 <summary class="font-black text-slate-900 cursor-pointer flex justify-between items-center text-sm uppercase">How do I calculate Wh for airline compliance?<span class="text-brandOrange group-open:rotate-180 transition">&#9660;</span></summary>
 <p class="faq-answer text-slate-600 text-sm leading-relaxed mt-4">Formula: Wh = mAh × Nominal Voltage ÷ 1000. Example: 27000mAh × 3.7V ÷ 1000 = 99.9Wh (just under the 100Wh carry-on limit). Batteries 100-160Wh need airline approval; above 160Wh are prohibited. All WOWOHCOOL models are designed at or below 99.9Wh.</p>
 </details>
 </div>
 </div>
</section>

